name: 04-Model-Training-and-Evaluation
content:
Model Training and Evaluation


Objective:

The objective of this guide is to provide an overview of training and evaluating the machine learning model for predicting Production Water Over-Demand using Random Forest Regression.


Overview of Random Forest Regression:

Random Forest Regression is an ensemble learning technique that builds multiple decision trees during training and combines their outputs to improve predictive performance. By averaging the predictions of individual trees, Random Forest minimizes overfitting, improves robustness, and delivers higher accuracy.


Model Training


1. Data Preprocessing

  • Data Cleaning
  • Handled missing values.
  • Removed duplicate records.
  • Corrected inconsistencies across water usage and abstraction fields.
  • Feature Engineering
  • Derived metrics such as abstraction-to-demand ratios and industry-specific water usage proportions.
  • Encoded categorical variables (e.g., month names, day of week) into numerical form.
  • Standardized/normalized numerical features to ensure consistency in scale.

2. Model Training

  • Constructed a Random Forest Regression model with an ensemble of decision trees.
  • Each tree was trained on a random subset of features and data samples to enhance diversity.
  • Key hyperparameters tuned included:
  • n_estimators: Number of trees in the forest.
  • max_depth: Maximum depth of each tree.
  • min_samples_split: Minimum number of samples required to split a node.
  • min_samples_leaf: Minimum number of samples required at a leaf node.

3. Target Variable

  • Excess_Usage â†’ Binary/continuous indicator of whether water demand exceeded expected levels.
  • The model aims to predict this outcome based on operational, infrastructural, and industrial factors.



Evaluation

The evaluation metrics revealed that the Random Forest Regression model delivers accurate predictions with minimal error, showcasing its ability to handle complex datasets with multiple features.


Prediction:

The trained Random Forest Regression model is deployed to predict over-demand scenarios based on input features. The model helps identify potential water over-demand incidents, enabling proactive resource management
